</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9B10261B0D9F08CD3FB666615EEDC61C" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="C67EA6942411827DD4413BD1917120A4" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C841233A092FA9C038886E593619C5A3" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">
Russia. Prov. Sanct-Petersburg: 5 km australi-occidentum, 26 June 1997, N.N. Tzvelev N-257 (conserved type, designated by 
<bibRefCitation id="141875EC49139B8B6A3579AAB3EB3BCB" DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/1224640" author="Soreng, RJ" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" pagination="157 - 159" refId="B20" refString="Soreng, RJ, Barrie, FR, 1999. (1391) Proposal to conserve the name Poa pratensis (Poaceae) with a conserved type. Taxon 48 (1): 157 - 159, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/1224640" title="(1391) Proposal to conserve the name Poa pratensis (Poaceae) with a conserved type." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/1224640" volume="48" year="1999">Soreng and Barrie 1999</bibRefCitation>
: 157: BM!; isotypes: B!, C!, CAN!, CONC!, H!, K!, KW!, L!, LE!, LIV!, MA!, MO!, MW!, NSW!, P!, PE!, PR!, S!, SI!, TNS!, US (US3456252!), W!).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6536582649220CCFFBDCDE29BF596E4D" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" type="many heterotypic synonyms">
<paragraph id="D5221E0F09AD736D2B0140D769B9153C" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Many heterotypic synonyms.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="685D29644D86F1A8480209810098B4ED" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">
- 
<taxonomicName id="4DDE0DA7949CD420339F8A9EA1A0B381" genus="P." lsidName="P. subsp. sect." pageId="0" pageNumber="27" rank="section" section="Poa" species="pratensis" subSpecies="sect.">P. sect. Poa</taxonomicName>
. Type, 
<taxonomicName id="DEE047AFFEE8C977F337F82A05F8D917" genus="P." lsidName="P. pratensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" rank="species" species="pratensis">
<emphasis id="98922DE771274D985A53169A53D3BDE1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">P. pratensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. (Type of genus 
<taxonomicName id="9A36B71BFF3B76E978D1069BB96E37AB" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa" order="Poales" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9C7C86F8496D03F8065B22F31818BA7E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Poa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L.)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E8501D1F9ACD111DF9E5BB450A633872" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="D41659B24C2F432CBC46F67BFCB562AF" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D216D14E14D95DCE7256F96B651D485A" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">widespread in Lesotho and South Africa. Introduced, mainly from European sources, native and widespread in Eurasia (also native in part in North America) and now around the world.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E895DD5DC8F7A014CB74688D72D26211" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" type="ecology">
<paragraph id="A2054257B586B32074E9319F6332DBD9" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="235B5E005D984659DF16A62A3D9BCBFE" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">cool temperate to subarctic, mesic habitats.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2832F077109E65AB4FC5C1716F6F6CAD" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" type="flowering">
<paragraph id="AC3671DF955B464BB7C3A5B163840BFE" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Flowering.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B0AC9C993E4686E49D3036C89D6B6A61" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">late spring early summer, to late summer at high elevations.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DC0D125BBD8EE82C6F299AB8B65F8B9C" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" type="vouchers">
<paragraph id="A921C8A0F809534BC2C05296D6B892D4" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Vouchers.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="79F63730E7A39B934C5E90D2EC371E4B" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis id="2AAE19D35741C95FE4076BF8EA9DBBC5" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Lesotho</emphasis>
. West of Sehlabathebe National Park, on grassy slopes above the Leqooa-Legowa river, 
<geoCoordinate id="8F582941B09254DC2CD01CADF2E12206" degrees="29.859179" direction="south" orientation="latitude" precision="1" value="-29.859179">S29.859179</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate id="57382D8A648559F809EF9244AED91FF1" degrees="29.055580" direction="east" orientation="longitude" precision="1" value="29.05558">E29.055580</geoCoordinate>
, 2310 m alt., sandstone substrate, mesic soil on steep grassy W facing slopes, 21 Feb 2020, S.P. Sylvester et al. 3571 (US). 
<emphasis id="DCE56E6C31CC22530DAB14B94D6F5660" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">South Africa</emphasis>
. Eastern Cape: Naudes Nek pass, near Rhodes, in grassland next to radio tower, 
<geoCoordinate id="9670BFBEEBEEC1F162FB5D91D810123D" degrees="30.765121" direction="south" orientation="latitude" precision="1" value="-30.765121">S30.765121</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate id="9E81669BEBF69E85C444C2FDD456C379" degrees="28.092349" direction="east" orientation="longitude" precision="1" value="28.092348">E28.092349</geoCoordinate>
, 2585 m alt., basaltic substrate, alpine tussock grassland transitioning to low shrubland dominated by 
<taxonomicName id="0A6922060CA2291B0FD188F6AAEB9C75" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Erica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Erica" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E709B750521425889DF92030947835D5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Erica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="115785FCCBD5076A8D781698808AFEA8" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Helichrysum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Helichrysum" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="60DA0D5AEAE37128F72E0EC3EAE235E5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Helichrysum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, fairly heavily grazed by sheep and cattle, gently sloping, moderately deep soil, 13 Feb 2020, S.P. Sylvester et al. 3499 (PRE, US).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2458C01EFBE455CE6ED9E394642691DA" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" type="notes">
<paragraph id="2BC1CB8856F7C6F957F7399BD917B8AF" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8AD6F7A1DE39E0340A8925E418F82FD1" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">
There are three major subspecies recognised in 
<taxonomicName id="FC08332A772397E6BC4C59CCF1DD57F9" authorityName="L., Sp. Pl. 1: 67 - 68" authorityYear="1753" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa pratensis" order="Poales" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pratensis">
<emphasis id="F6E3A42D9FFFAD5E4611AF5555FF99A8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Poa pratensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: subsp. 
<taxonomicName id="5DBFC36365279CEEBB6EAB2937BE2996" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="subsp. angustifolia" order="Poales" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="pratensis" subSpecies="angustifolia">angustifolia</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="5DE03DF75C488469323BF6FAC5C22CF6" authorityName="Lindm" authorityYear="1905" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="irrigata" order="Poales" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="irrigata">
<emphasis id="845E1E5D8F13AD64F6B75F97303EB77C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">irrigata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="D4F5E3BF4F01E31BA89409153A580AFC" authorityName="L., Sp. Pl. 1: 67 - 68" authorityYear="1753" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="pratensis" order="Poales" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pratensis">
<emphasis id="8062AAB4739E10FE16EFB8736DD3767A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">pratensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Intermediate specimens are common and difficult to place. 
<bibRefCitation id="7CA41E56B2A9DF713D1ACCB8DF65F7BC" author="Cope, TA" journalOrPublisher="Botanical Society of the British Isles Handbook" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" pagination="5 - 612" refId="B8" refString="Cope, TA, Gray, A, 2009. Grasses of the British Isles. Botanical Society of the British Isles Handbook 13 (1): 5 - 612" title="Grasses of the British Isles." volume="13" year="2009">Cope and Gray (2009)</bibRefCitation>
provide a good account of the distinctions, also see 
<bibRefCitation id="FD2A2577EC531E1C1271AEFC9DC8ACFE" author="Soreng, RJ" journalOrPublisher="Willdenowia" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" refId="B19" refString="Soreng, RJ, 2007. 14.13 Poa L. In: BarkworthMECapelsKMLongSAndertonLKPiepMB (Eds) Flora of North America, North of Mexico. Oxford University Press, New York.24: 486-601." title="14.13 Poa L. In: BarkworthMECapelsKMLongSAndertonLKPiepMB (Eds) Flora of North America, North of Mexico. Oxford University Press, New York. 24: 486 - 601." year="2007">Soreng (2007)</bibRefCitation>
. Facultatively apomictic. 2 
<emphasis id="79AD43D616D0D30C77BD3B328BA5BA87" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">n</emphasis>
= 21-147 (including nearly every number in between). - 
<emphasis id="7593190ACAA56C400AC0DF7EAE51D7BF" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Php</emphasis>
genotype.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
